[[File:Brazilian Honda Civic Flex car 09 2008 logo & secondary gas tank.jpg|thumb|right|The Brazilian 2008 [[Honda Civic]] Flex has outside access to the secondary gasoline reservoir tank from the outside, shown by the arrow in the front right side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmotors.com.br/wmpublicador/Segredos_Conteudo.vxlpub?hnid=36913|title=Honda apresenta Fit e Civic Flex|publisher=WebMotors|date=2006-10-18|author=Gustavo Henrique Ruffo|accessdate=2008-10-15|language=Portuguese}}</ref>]]
Brazilian flex cars are capable of running on just [[hydrated]] ethanol (E100), or just on a blend of gasoline with 20 to 25%[[anhydrous]] ethanol, or on any arbitrary combination of both fuels.<ref name="SusEthanol">{{Cite book | last = Goettemoeller, Jeffrey; Adrian Goettemoeller | title = Sustainable Ethanol: Biofuels, Biorefineries, Cellulosic Biomass, Flex-Fuel Vehicles, and Sustainable Farming for Energy Independence | year = 2007| publisher = Prairie Oak Publishing, Maryville, Missouri |pages=56<U+2013>61 |language=| isbn = 978-0-9786293-0-4 }}</ref> Pure gasoline is no longer sold in the country because these high ethanol blends are mandatory since 1993.<ref name="Portaria2007">{{cite web|url=http://extranet.agricultura.gov.br/sislegis-consulta/consultarLegislacao.do?operacao=visualizar&id=17886|title=Portaria N<U+00BA> 143, de 27 de Junho de 2007|publisher=Minist<U+00E9>rio da Agricultura, Pecu<U+00E1>ria e Abastecimento|accessdate=2008-10-05|language=Portuguese}} This decree fixed the mandatory blend at 25% starting July 1st, 2007</ref><ref name="Lei8723">{{cite web|url=http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil/leis/L8723.htm|title=Lei N<U+00BA> 8.723, de 28 de Outubro de 1993. Disp<U+00F5>e sobre a redu<U+00E7><U+00E3>o de emiss<U+00E3>o de poluentes por ve<U+00ED>culos automotores e d<U+00E1> outras provid<U+00EA>ncias|publisher=Casa Civil da Presid<U+00EA>ncia da Rep<U+00FA>blica|accessdate=2008-10-05|language=Portuguese}} See article 9<U+00BA> and modifications approved by Law N<U+00BA> 10.696, 2003-07-02 increasing the upper limit to 25%</ref> Therefore, all Brazilian automakers have optimized flex vehicles to run with gasoline blends from E20 to E25, and with a few exceptions, these FFVs are unable to run smoothly with pure gasoline which causes [[engine knocking]], as vehicles traveling to neighboring [[South America]]n countries have demonstrated.<ref name="4Rodas">{{cite web|url=http://quatrorodas.abril.com.br/colunas/conteudo_206186.shtml |title=Receita caseira para rodar fora do pa<U+00ED>s sem problemas ao abastecer|author=Bob Sharp|accessdate=2008-10-04|publisher=Revista Quatro Rodas |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Only two models are specifically built with a flex-fuel engine optimized to operate also with pure gasoline (E0), the [[Renault Clio|Renault Clio Hi-Flex]]<ref name="4Rodas"/><ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.parana-online.com.br/canal/automoveis/news/104963/ | author=A.C. Bispo|title=Clio Hi-Flex impressiona pelo desempenho |publisher=Parana Online | date=2008-07-19|accessdate=2008-10-05|language=Portuguese}}</ref> and the [[Fiat Siena|Fiat Siena Tetrafuel]].<ref name="Christine Lepisto">{{cite web|url=http://www.treehugger.com/files/2006/08/fiat_sienna_tetr.php|title= Fiat Siena Tetra Power: Your Choice of Four Fuels |publisher=Treehugger|author= Christine Lepisto|date=2006-08-27 |accessdate=2008-08-24|language= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.caradisiac.com/Nouvelle-Fiat-Siena-2008-sans-complexe-359 |author= |title=Nouvelle Fiat Siena 2008: sans complexe|publisher=Caradisiac |date=2007-11-01|accessdate=2008-08-31 |language=French|archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20080701042346/http://news.caradisiac.com/Nouvelle-Fiat-Siena-2008-sans-complexe-359 |archivedate = July 01, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

The flexibility of Brazilian FFVs empowers the consumers to choose the fuel depending on current market prices. As ethanol [[Fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] is lower than gasoline because of ethanol's energy content is close to 34% less per unit volume than gasoline,<ref>www.eia.doe.gov [http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/alternate/page/faq.html#12 DOE FAQ]</ref><ref name="EEREFAQ">www.eere.energy.gov [http://www.eere.energy.gov/afdc/progs/ddown.cgi?afdc/FAQ/5/0/0 Energy.gov site]</ref><ref name="EIAATTF">www.eia.doe.gov [http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/solar.renewables/alt_trans_fuel/attf.pdf#page=39 Alternative Fuel Efficiencies in Miles per Gallon]</ref> flex cars running on ethanol get a lower mileage than when running on pure gasoline. However, this effect is partially offset by the usually lower price per liter of ethanol fuel. As a [[rule of thumb]], Brazilian consumers are frequently advised by the media to use more alcohol than gasoline in their mix only when ethanol prices are 30% lower or more than gasoline, as ethanol price fluctuates heavily depending on the result of seasonal sugar cane harvests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://opiniaoweb.com/portal/alcool-ou-gasolina-saiba-qual-escolher-quando-for-abastecer/ |title=<U+00C1>lcool ou Gasolina? Saiba qual escolher quando for abastecer |author=JB Online |date=2007-11-20|publisher=Opinaoweb|accessdate=2008-08-24|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igf.com.br/aprende/dicas/dicasResp.aspx?dica_Id=1435 |title=Saiba o que fazer para economizar gasolina|author=InfoMoney |date=2007-05-30 |publisher=IGF |accessdate=2008-08-24 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>

